#X text 450 57 As a line generator \, [vline~] can also convert floats to signals with a smoothening ramp. A simpler version of this object is [line~] \, which can do the same. You can set the ramp time as the 2nd item in a list input for both cases. Note \, however \, that [line~] will start and end all lines at the beggining and end of audio blocks \, while [vline~] is more accurate and lines will have precisely the given time. The [vline~] can also schedule different ramps. Check its help fi \; le., f 53;
#X text 463 392 The [float2sig~] object from ELSE is an abstraction based on [vline~] and takes a ramp time as an argument. It can be abbreviatted as [f2s~], f 51;
#X text 26 205 But then we have the [vline~] object \, which offers a more accurate conversion. It is mostly a line/envelope generator as we'll see \, but it can also be used for this type of conversion. Single values are zero length lines and are immediately converted to signals., f 55;
